{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Histatins are small molecular weight proteins produced by the human salivary glands that exhibit antifungal and antibacterial activities [[cite:PUB00073976]]. They are also components of the acquired enamel pellicle (AEP) [[cite:PUB00073979]]. Histatins 1 and 3 are full-length peptides of 38 and 32 amino acid residues respectively; other characterised members of the histatin family are proteolytic products formed during secretion [[cite:PUB00073976], [cite:PUB00073983], [cite:PUB00073990]]. The predominant histatins are histatin 1, 3, and 5; histatin 5 is a proteolytic product of histatin 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Statherin is a 43-residue peptide, secreted by parotid and submandibular glands. It is a multifunctional molecule that prevents calcium phosphate precipitation in saliva, thus maintaining a high calcium and phosphate levels [[cite:PUB00073993], [cite:PUB00008460]]. Moreover, statherin and its C-terminal fragments inhibit the growth of anaerobic bacteria from the oral cavity [[cite:PUB00073995]]. Statherin and histatin 1 reduce Streptococcus mutans adhesion onto hydroxyapatite surfaces [[cite:PUB00073988]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR15057" "STATHERIN"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Histatin/statherin family", "short" "Histatin/statherin"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 37, "taxa" 166, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 131, "sets" 0, "proteins" 131, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 111}, "pathways" 1}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR030773", :literature {"PUB00073990" {"URL" nil, "issue" "2", "authors" ["Sabatini LM" "Azen EA."], "ISO_journal" "Biochem. Biophys. Res. Commun.", "DOI_URL" "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0006-291X(89)92460-1", "medl